<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-02-09T19:14:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-02-09T19:14:00-05:00" n="195" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d195">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">320/2–953: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United
                                Nations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lodge</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                                <lb/><gloss target="#t_niact1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                                </gloss></seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-02-09T19:14:00-05:00">February
                                    9, 1953—7:14 p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>493. Re items on <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> agenda.</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                        <p>4. The appointment of a secretary general seems to me a particularly
                            delicate negotiating problem. The alternatives seem to be whether there
                            can be agreement on a new secretary general satisfactory to us or
                            whether there must be an acting secretary general appointed by the
                            Assembly. It is too early to say which solution will occur and precisely
                            how to go about seeing to it that an individual satisfactory to us is
                            finally agreed upon. At this time, however, I see disadvantages in the
                            US joining any active group in promoting any particular candidate.</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lodge</hi>
                                </persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>